1
00:02:54,273 --> 00:02:55,766
Good morning.
- Good morning, Sir.

2
00:02:57,815 --> 00:02:58,561
Good morning.

3
00:02:58,733 --> 00:03:00,558
Good morning. I just came to look around.

4
00:03:00,734 --> 00:03:02,274
Yes, sir.
- All right if I go below?

5
00:03:02,483 --> 00:03:04,224
Certainly, sir. Can I get you some coffee?

6
00:03:04,399 --> 00:03:06,889
No, I'll just go below and wait
for the captain. Maybe later.

7
00:03:07,067 --> 00:03:08,097
Well, sir.
- Chief.

8
00:03:10,610 --> 00:03:11,640
Who's he?

9
00:03:12,778 --> 00:03:14,768
That's Sherman.
- Yes?

10
00:03:15,360 --> 00:03:17,731
And what is he doing here at six in the morning?

11
00:03:17,902 --> 00:03:21,436
He came to make sure that you were comfortable.

12
00:03:22,446 --> 00:03:24,270
Don't you know anything about submarines?

13
00:03:24,446 --> 00:03:27,646
Yes, sure. I know Sherman. He's the boss of Submarines Pacific.

14
00:03:27,821 --> 00:03:30,985
He was the first captain of this boat.
- Yes, I know that.

15
00:03:31,155 --> 00:03:34,070
Then you should be able to figure out what he is doing here.

16
00:03:36,532 --> 00:03:39,020
If you were the first skipper of the "Sea Tiger"…

17
00:03:39,240 --> 00:03:43,649
… and you ordered her sent to the junkyard at nine…

18
00:03:43,990 --> 00:03:46,147
... what would you be doing at six?

19
00:04:29,208 --> 00:04:33,333
USN SEA TIGER
CAPTAIN'S JOURNAL

20
00:04:33,876 --> 00:04:36,163
December 10, 1941.

21
00:04:36,334 --> 00:04:39,619
Moored starboard side to Machina Wharf. Cavite Navy Yard…

22
00:04:39,794 --> 00:04:42,662
… Philippine Islands, for provisions and fuel.

23
00:04:42,877 --> 00:04:45,284
Directive received from Commander Asiatic Fleet…

24
00:04:45,462 --> 00:04:48,461
"You will sink or destroy all enemy ships wherever encountered. "

25
00:04:49,087 --> 00:04:52,039
Have advised Commander Submarine Force, Asiatic Fleet... .

26
00:04:52,214 --> 00:04:53,411
that "Sea Tiger"…

27
00:04:53,589 --> 00:04:57,002
…will be ready for sea at 19:00, 10 December 1941.

28
00:04:57,423 --> 00:05:00,458
Captain! Captain!

29
00:05:00,965 --> 00:05:02,292
Enemy planes over.

30
00:05:13,509 --> 00:05:15,963
Ready on engines?
- The best we can, Sir.

31
00:05:27,011 --> 00:05:28,292
Cut those lines!

32
00:05:44,057 --> 00:05:45,383
Take cover!

33
00:06:18,023 --> 00:06:20,725
I'm not denying we suffered minor damage, Sir, but…

34
00:06:20,897 --> 00:06:21,727
Minor damage??

35
00:06:22,107 --> 00:06:24,773
What does it take to convince you? You've been sunk!

36
00:06:25,482 --> 00:06:27,805
You ought to read your own report.
- Yes.

37
00:06:28,150 --> 00:06:31,018
“Bulkheads, main ballast tanks and pressure hull...

38
00:06:31,192 --> 00:06:32,566
… ripped by bomb fragments.

39
00:06:32,733 --> 00:06:35,768
Engine room flooded, main induction and ventilation wrecked…

40
00:06:35,943 --> 00:06:40,317
… torpedo tubes, motor controls and reduction gear inoperable…

41
00:06:40,527 --> 00:06:44,687
… electrical equipment, wiring, gauges, gyro, radio. "

42
00:06:44,986 --> 00:06:46,265
All you've got out there…

43
00:06:46,444 --> 00:06:50,226
… is a periscope sitting on a couple of thousand tons of scrap metal.

44
00:06:51,446 --> 00:06:52,855
What do you suggest, sir?

45
00:06:53,029 --> 00:06:56,064
Should we underwater weld to jury patch the hull before pumping her out…

46
00:06:56,239 --> 00:06:58,775
… or should we raise her first and then work on the hull?

47
00:06:58,948 --> 00:07:01,354
Matt, with major repairs
and a complete overhaul

48
00:07:01,532 --> 00:07:03,523
maybe Sea Tiger could be put back in commission.

49
00:07:03,698 --> 00:07:06,366
A functioning Navy yard might do it.
- Sir.

50
00:07:06,532 --> 00:07:10,479
My chiefs are pretty good hands.
They know they're on their own.

51
00:07:10,658 --> 00:07:13,147
and what we're up against. But we think we
can get " Sea Tiger " back in the war.

52
00:07:13,326 --> 00:07:14,818
Yes, on who's side?

53
00:07:14,992 --> 00:07:19,368
We're due to evacuate back to Bataan on the 26th...

54
00:07:19,536 --> 00:07:23,530
... two weeks to do a job a yard couldn't do in two months.

55
00:07:23,743 --> 00:07:27,608
We don't think we can get her into
fighting trim right away...

56
00:07:27,786 --> 00:07:31,449
repair it... just enough to
reach the nearest sub tender.

57
00:07:31,620 --> 00:07:34,111
That would be the "Bushnell", in Darwin.

58
00:07:34,330 --> 00:07:36,534
... almost two thousand miles of ocean...

59
00:07:36,705 --> 00:07:38,993
with the Japanese Navy roaming over it.

60
00:07:39,165 --> 00:07:42,861
And you're going to make it in a sub
held together with spit and bailing wire?

61
00:07:43,165 --> 00:07:44,077
Sir...

62
00:07:44,248 --> 00:07:46,998
... the " Sea Tiger " deserves
a better epitaph than...

63
00:07:47,165 --> 00:07:49,950
... "commissioned 1940,
sunk, 1941.

64
00:07:50,124 --> 00:07:52,081
Engagements: none.
Shots fired: none. "

65
00:07:52,251 --> 00:07:54,620
You can't let her go that way, it's like...

66
00:07:54,792 --> 00:07:58,290
... a beautiful woman dying an old
maid, if know what I mean...

67
00:07:58,461 --> 00:07:59,739
... by an old maid.

68
00:08:00,167 --> 00:08:03,119
Did you ever sell used cars?
- No, sir.

69
00:08:03,377 --> 00:08:05,533
I think you missed your calling.

70
00:08:05,920 --> 00:08:09,368
Okay, Matt. You've got two weeks
to get her out or we blow her up.

71
00:08:09,545 --> 00:08:10,576
Fair enough.

72
00:08:12,004 --> 00:08:12,869
By the way...

73
00:08:13,046 --> 00:08:16,294
... three of my officers and eighteen
men have been transferred...

74
00:08:16,465 --> 00:08:18,787
... How soon can I can get them back?
- You don't.

75
00:08:18,963 --> 00:08:21,001
You'll have to get by with a skeleton crew.

76
00:08:21,172 --> 00:08:23,127
I'll get you what replacements I can.

77
00:08:23,340 --> 00:08:25,462
Yes, sir. Thank you, sir.

78
00:09:04,889 --> 00:09:06,134
All done.

79
00:09:09,015 --> 00:09:12,511
Men, clean up later.
That's all we can do now.

80
00:09:12,850 --> 00:09:14,509
An odd job but might hold alright.

81
00:09:14,684 --> 00:09:15,465
Yes, sir.

82
00:09:33,314 --> 00:09:35,469
Do you think the No. 2 tank will hold?

83
00:09:36,188 --> 00:09:38,393
All that we can do is try, sir.

84
00:09:39,688 --> 00:09:41,062
Which one are you holding?
- The left.

85
00:09:41,230 --> 00:09:42,179
Well hang on.

86
00:09:42,356 --> 00:09:44,182
Okay, give her some air.

87
00:10:18,696 --> 00:10:20,817
I found it, I found it!

88
00:10:21,863 --> 00:10:24,269
Found it. Look.
- I give up. What is it?

89
00:10:24,446 --> 00:10:25,906
The cake that my mother sent me.

90
00:10:26,073 --> 00:10:29,486
Isn't that nice. Take it to the
cook, maybe he'll warm it up.

91
00:10:32,282 --> 00:10:33,313
Mothers.

92
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:36,356
Why couldn't she send
something we need?

93
00:10:36,534 --> 00:10:38,571
Like a universal coupling joint.

94
00:10:46,744 --> 00:10:47,987
What is it, Molumphry?

95
00:10:48,369 --> 00:10:49,743
I do not know, sir.

96
00:10:49,953 --> 00:10:51,150
Have a look.

97
00:10:56,661 --> 00:10:58,487
Looks like the Good Humor man.

98
00:10:58,662 --> 00:11:01,412
I wonder if he left his tie off.
- What's going on?

99
00:11:02,788 --> 00:11:04,744
Take a look, sir.
- Okay.

100
00:11:07,165 --> 00:11:08,196
Holy moly.

101
00:11:18,583 --> 00:11:19,958
What is it?

102
00:11:20,126 --> 00:11:24,073
I hope I'm wrong, but with that suitcase
I'd say he was one of the replacements.

103
00:11:24,626 --> 00:11:26,084
Don't tell me that!

104
00:11:27,086 --> 00:11:28,828
Oh, for heaven's sake!
- Do you know anything about him?

105
00:11:29,003 --> 00:11:32,204
Only from the society pages
of the Honolulu newspapers;...

106
00:11:32,628 --> 00:11:35,295
His name is Lieutenant Nick Holden.
- Holden.

107
00:11:35,462 --> 00:11:37,666
He's the darling of the
high-class social set.

108
00:11:37,837 --> 00:11:40,706
I'll bet he is.
- He and the Admiral's wife...

109
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:43,748
won the rumba championship
two years in a row!

110
00:12:08,052 --> 00:12:11,051
Okay, fellows. Come on,
knock it off. Back to work.

111
00:12:22,097 --> 00:12:24,171
Lieutenant Nick Holden,
reporting for duty, sir.

112
00:12:25,596 --> 00:12:27,838
Excuse the misunderstanding,
Mr. Holden...

113
00:12:28,015 --> 00:12:30,884
It's unusual to see an Admiral's
aide without the Admiral.

114
00:12:31,058 --> 00:12:34,387
He was scheduled to be transferred. I was
sent to make arrangements...

115
00:12:34,557 --> 00:12:36,881
then the war broke out...
- And you're stranded?

116
00:12:37,058 --> 00:12:39,593
Yes, sir. Captain Henderson
assigned me to you...

117
00:12:39,767 --> 00:12:42,337
He said to hurry...
before you left.

118
00:12:42,558 --> 00:12:44,135
The bearings are okay sir...

119
00:12:44,308 --> 00:12:47,641
but if we don't come up with
an oil pump shaft we will only...

120
00:12:47,811 --> 00:12:50,893
... get out of here by rowing.
- Didn't Hunkle follow up the requisition?

121
00:12:51,061 --> 00:12:53,811
Requisition? That's all we do.
But we never get anything.

122
00:12:53,978 --> 00:12:56,347
We might as well write
a letter to Santa Claus.

123
00:12:56,604 --> 00:12:58,808
Ya. Well, thank you, Tostin.

124
00:13:01,105 --> 00:13:03,594
Have you ever been in a submarine?
- No, sir.

125
00:13:03,772 --> 00:13:07,601
We need a torpedo and gunnery
officer. Any experience?

126
00:13:07,773 --> 00:13:10,309
Guns? I'm afraid not, sir.
- How about navigation?

127
00:13:10,482 --> 00:13:12,188
Terribly sorry.
- Communications?

128
00:13:12,358 --> 00:13:13,767
Wish I could help, sir.

129
00:13:14,190 --> 00:13:15,138
Tell me.

130
00:13:15,316 --> 00:13:18,349
Before becoming an Admiral's aide
What did you do in the navy?

131
00:13:18,524 --> 00:13:20,811
Well, sir, I was primarily an
idea man.

132
00:13:20,983 --> 00:13:22,357
I see. Well...

133
00:13:22,776 --> 00:13:25,100
Tell me - what does
an idea man do?

134
00:13:25,568 --> 00:13:28,271
I coordinated the Navy day
parade in Milwaukee...

135
00:13:29,069 --> 00:13:32,316
... and I was the special liaison officer
for the Eleventh Naval District.

136
00:13:32,486 --> 00:13:34,227
Liaison? With what?
- Hollywood.

137
00:13:35,277 --> 00:13:38,146
I coordinated the design
of admission posters.

138
00:13:38,320 --> 00:13:41,235
From there I transferred to
Fleet Headquarters Honolulu.

139
00:13:42,654 --> 00:13:44,396
Is that where they gave you sea duty?

140
00:13:44,572 --> 00:13:48,104
No, sir. I was the Recreation Officer
at the Royal Arms Hotel.

141
00:13:49,406 --> 00:13:50,781
Just for my information...

142
00:13:50,949 --> 00:13:53,566
... What does an idea man
do in a hotel?

143
00:13:53,990 --> 00:13:56,859
The Navy took over the hotel
for officer's training...

144
00:13:57,033 --> 00:13:59,107
and I saw that
entertainment was provided.

145
00:13:59,282 --> 00:14:02,234
Have you ever been to sea?
- Yes, sir, destroyer duty.

146
00:14:02,491 --> 00:14:05,988
How did you find time for it?
- It was a mistake, sir.

147
00:14:06,284 --> 00:14:09,070
A week after I left Honolulu
they got it straightened out.

148
00:14:09,243 --> 00:14:11,448
Who, the Admiral or
the Admiral's wife?

149
00:14:11,619 --> 00:14:13,775
She must be upset
with you out here ;...

150
00:14:13,953 --> 00:14:16,655
that will cost her the rumba
championship this year.

151
00:14:16,828 --> 00:14:17,942
Holy!

152
00:14:20,913 --> 00:14:24,823
Here you go, my man. Will you take
this bag and clubs to the submarine?

153
00:14:24,996 --> 00:14:26,027
Thank you, son.

154
00:14:40,125 --> 00:14:41,155
Hunkle.

155
00:14:41,375 --> 00:14:42,952
What about that oil pump?

156
00:14:43,125 --> 00:14:44,952
Well, I put in four requisitions.

157
00:14:45,126 --> 00:14:47,793
Did you put stamp them urgent?
- I put a requisition in for one, sir.

158
00:14:47,960 --> 00:14:50,626
For what?
- An urgent stamp, we haven't got one.

159
00:14:50,793 --> 00:14:52,700
Haven't we received anything
from supplies?

160
00:14:52,877 --> 00:14:54,500
The only requisition
that's been filled

161
00:14:54,669 --> 00:14:56,659
is the requisition
for more requisition paper.

162
00:14:56,962 --> 00:14:59,497
Captain, I got the trim pump broken
down. Want to look at it?

163
00:14:59,670 --> 00:15:01,211
Yes.
- All right, Hunkle.

164
00:15:02,880 --> 00:15:04,159
Can I help you, sir?

165
00:15:05,047 --> 00:15:07,452
No, not really. My name
is Lt. Nick Holden.

166
00:15:07,631 --> 00:15:09,918
I'm Ernest Hunkle.
- Pleasure to meet you.

167
00:15:10,422 --> 00:15:11,667
Would care for some coffee?

168
00:15:12,338 --> 00:15:14,246
Yes, thank you.
- Follow me.

169
00:15:22,341 --> 00:15:25,043
Who is that?
- It's " The Prophet ", sir.

170
00:15:27,885 --> 00:15:29,342
His he always that cheerful?

171
00:15:29,510 --> 00:15:31,383
That's just the way he is, sir.
Don't mind him.

172
00:15:31,552 --> 00:15:33,293
Cream and sugar?
- Yes, thank you.

173
00:15:33,468 --> 00:15:35,791
"Why even try?...

174
00:15:36,051 --> 00:15:39,418
If you're lucky enough...

175
00:15:39,595 --> 00:15:43,127
to live through today...

176
00:15:43,679 --> 00:15:47,093
tomorrow... ...

177
00:15:47,264 --> 00:15:51,093
... you will die. "

178
00:15:52,013 --> 00:15:53,175
I don't know...

179
00:15:54,014 --> 00:15:57,380
From the looks of things around here
he knows what he's singing about.

180
00:15:57,598 --> 00:15:59,305
Your coffee, sir.
- Thank you.

181
00:15:59,473 --> 00:16:01,929
Excuse me, I must get back to my work.
- Certainly.

182
00:16:02,100 --> 00:16:03,129
Thank you.

183
00:16:12,393 --> 00:16:13,388
Sir.

184
00:16:14,143 --> 00:16:16,467
Sir. Look at this.
- What?

185
00:16:16,645 --> 00:16:19,679
Last June, when we were
here, I requisitioned toilet paper.

186
00:16:19,854 --> 00:16:22,306
Every time we've been back
I sent through a follow up...

187
00:16:22,478 --> 00:16:26,557
... according to the book through channels
I even submitted a sample.

188
00:16:26,731 --> 00:16:27,761
So what happens?

189
00:16:27,939 --> 00:16:32,097
They responded : " Cannot identify,
requisition cancelled ".

190
00:16:32,856 --> 00:16:36,303
Not that I'm complaining, sir,
but this what I've been going through.

191
00:16:36,482 --> 00:16:38,603
All right, Hunkle.
Relax...

192
00:16:39,148 --> 00:16:40,393
... Take a letter.

193
00:16:41,441 --> 00:16:42,472
Let's see.

194
00:16:43,358 --> 00:16:45,182
Are you ready?
- Yes, sir.

195
00:16:45,484 --> 00:16:48,102
From Commanding Officer
" USS Sea Tiger "...

196
00:16:48,526 --> 00:16:51,689
To Supply Officer, Navy Yard,
Cavite, Philippines...

197
00:16:52,318 --> 00:16:55,518
Dear Commander Submarine
Forces, etc...

198
00:16:56,235 --> 00:16:58,984
Subject : Toilet paper.

199
00:17:00,153 --> 00:17:01,101
One:. .

200
00:17:01,320 --> 00:17:04,484
... on 6 June, 1941...

201
00:17:04,696 --> 00:17:08,690
... this vessel submitted a requisition
for 150 rolls of toilet paper...

202
00:17:09,197 --> 00:17:12,609
... On 16 December, 1941...

203
00:17:12,822 --> 00:17:15,441
the requisition was returned
with stamped notation...

204
00:17:15,614 --> 00:17:18,447
"can not identify material required".

205
00:17:19,615 --> 00:17:20,528
Two :. .

206
00:17:20,740 --> 00:17:23,573
The Commanding Officer of the
" USS Sea Tiger "...

207
00:17:23,950 --> 00:17:26,154
can not help but wonder
what is being used...

208
00:17:26,325 --> 00:17:30,401
at Cavite as a substitute for
this unidentifiable material...

209
00:17:30,575 --> 00:17:32,566
once so well known
to this command.

210
00:17:33,785 --> 00:17:35,611
Three :. . 
- Excuse me, sir.

211
00:17:36,118 --> 00:17:38,239
What?
- Excuse me for interrupting.

212
00:17:38,870 --> 00:17:41,239
Have you ever been to Las Vegas?
- Why?

213
00:17:41,411 --> 00:17:44,114
The boys up there would say you're
trying to make your point the hard way.

214
00:17:44,287 --> 00:17:47,119
Putting in requisitions,
going through channels...

215
00:17:47,287 --> 00:17:49,410
You've got to sneak up
a few back alleys.

216
00:17:49,580 --> 00:17:53,111
You need a Supply Officer to
help you find those back alleys.

217
00:17:53,330 --> 00:17:54,658
You, Mr. Holden?
- Yes, sir.

218
00:17:54,831 --> 00:17:57,320
You'd ruin your manicure.
- Here.

219
00:17:58,582 --> 00:18:00,786
Don't let my manicure
fool you, sir.

220
00:18:01,500 --> 00:18:04,617
I grew up in a neighborhood
called " Noah's Ark ".

221
00:18:05,041 --> 00:18:07,329
If you didn't travel in pairs,
you didn't travel.

222
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:10,830
Why don't you make out a shopping list
and I'll see what's left at the market?

223
00:18:12,375 --> 00:18:15,327
You're not the volunteering
type. What's your angle?

224
00:18:15,544 --> 00:18:18,577
Same as yours. We both want
to get the submarine...

225
00:18:18,752 --> 00:18:21,621
... out of here. You so you
can fight your war...

226
00:18:21,962 --> 00:18:22,992
... and me...

227
00:18:23,420 --> 00:18:25,162
Well, let's say I'm an optimist.

228
00:18:25,337 --> 00:18:29,082
Wherever we're headed I am sure
I can get a better deal.

229
00:18:32,130 --> 00:18:34,915
Mr. Holden, I may regret this...

230
00:18:35,089 --> 00:18:37,957
... but you've just been
made my Supply Officer.

231
00:18:38,131 --> 00:18:40,039
Get your list from Hunkle.
- Thank you, sir.

232
00:18:40,215 --> 00:18:44,126
I am going to need a couple
of men. May I pick my own?

233
00:18:44,425 --> 00:18:47,173
Right.
- Thank you, sir.

234
00:18:50,634 --> 00:18:51,629
Hunkle...

235
00:18:51,801 --> 00:18:54,753
... I've got a list for you. We're
going shopping tonight.

236
00:19:05,638 --> 00:19:06,834
Turn on the lights.

237
00:19:20,014 --> 00:19:23,677
Look, gentlemen, I think
we hit pay dirt.

238
00:19:23,848 --> 00:19:25,094
Do you have the list?
- Yes, sir.

239
00:19:25,267 --> 00:19:28,134
Take the stuff we
need to the door.

240
00:19:28,308 --> 00:19:31,011
Let's go, we don't have much
time. Come on, guys.

241
00:19:31,225 --> 00:19:32,635
You grab the wire.

242
00:19:33,142 --> 00:19:35,217
I forgot something, sir.
- What did you forget?

243
00:19:35,393 --> 00:19:38,142
I never wrapped up my belongings
for my kinfolk...

244
00:19:38,310 --> 00:19:40,597
... if we don't get back.
- Will you stop talking like that?

245
00:19:42,270 --> 00:19:44,344
They're going to find us and
shoot us down like a dog.

246
00:19:44,520 --> 00:19:46,393
Will you shut up?
- Alright, Hunkle.

247
00:19:46,563 --> 00:19:49,228
He's got the right idea;
so be very careful.

248
00:19:49,395 --> 00:19:53,057
Get it to the door.
- Don't forget what you promised ;...

249
00:19:54,479 --> 00:19:57,893
When the shooting starts turn your back
so Gertie won't get splattered.

250
00:20:00,356 --> 00:20:01,351
Who is Gertie?

251
00:20:01,524 --> 00:20:03,431
You don't know about Gertie?
- Shut up.

252
00:20:03,608 --> 00:20:05,349
Get moving with that thing.

253
00:20:08,733 --> 00:20:09,976
Hunkle, who is Gertie?

254
00:20:10,149 --> 00:20:12,852
Molumphry will be
happy with this wiring.

255
00:20:14,900 --> 00:20:16,726
Hunkle, I asked you a question.

256
00:20:25,529 --> 00:20:26,560
Who is Gertie?

257
00:20:26,737 --> 00:20:28,726
The truth is that she's nobody.
- Hunkle.

258
00:20:32,028 --> 00:20:35,562
Well, sir, when my enlistment
was up last year, the boys...

259
00:20:35,738 --> 00:20:37,481
... gave me a farewell party.

260
00:20:37,822 --> 00:20:41,189
I do not usually drink, sir,
but that night I must have.

261
00:20:41,948 --> 00:20:43,490
The last thing I remember...

262
00:20:43,658 --> 00:20:46,443
... is standing in front of
a tattoo parlor...

263
00:20:55,118 --> 00:20:56,492
May I?

264
00:21:00,994 --> 00:21:04,858
They ought to hang you in the Louvre.
- I came home to marry...

265
00:21:05,120 --> 00:21:08,035
... but when I saw myself
in the mirror, I reenlisted.

266
00:21:08,621 --> 00:21:10,990
I never could explain
Gertie to my fiancée.

267
00:21:11,162 --> 00:21:13,947
No. I can see you've
got a problem.

268
00:21:15,498 --> 00:21:17,073
But look on the bright side ;...

269
00:21:17,247 --> 00:21:20,115
You've probably got the
sexiest chest in the Navy.

270
00:21:20,289 --> 00:21:21,452
Sir.
- Yes.

271
00:21:22,290 --> 00:21:25,158
I am not one to worry when
there's no need but...

272
00:21:25,583 --> 00:21:28,699
... after we get this stuff to the door,
how do we get it to the boat?

273
00:21:28,874 --> 00:21:32,406
Don't worry about that, just keep
your stuff... The police!

274
00:21:32,874 --> 00:21:35,115
<i>- Check the warehouses. </i>

275
00:21:54,004 --> 00:21:55,202
Halt!

276
00:21:59,839 --> 00:22:00,870
What's your business here?

277
00:22:01,048 --> 00:22:04,462
I stepped out for a breath of air.
- Let's see your identification.

278
00:22:04,632 --> 00:22:07,202
Certainly. Here you are.

279
00:22:08,382 --> 00:22:09,661
Lieutenant.

280
00:22:09,841 --> 00:22:11,120
Why black face, sir?

281
00:22:11,299 --> 00:22:14,501
Don't you know the penalty for
breaking blackout regulations?

282
00:22:14,676 --> 00:22:17,876
Blackout regulations?
- You read the order from Admiral Nimitz?

283
00:22:18,051 --> 00:22:20,836
No. What order?
- Regulation 4-1-9-8-2 :. .

284
00:22:21,010 --> 00:22:24,341
"... no navy personnel shall appear
at night without face camouflage. "

285
00:22:24,511 --> 00:22:28,800
A plane comes over, you look up,
give away our position.

286
00:22:29,011 --> 00:22:31,335
Sergeant, a face like that could
cause a lot of damage...

287
00:22:31,513 --> 00:22:33,254
... I'll have to put you on report.

288
00:22:33,430 --> 00:22:35,634
Honestly, sir, no
one told me about it.

289
00:22:36,138 --> 00:22:37,549
Alright, you've been told.

290
00:22:39,056 --> 00:22:40,761
Black out that face, Sgt.

291
00:22:41,097 --> 00:22:43,135
Yes, sir. Thank you, sir.

292
00:22:58,351 --> 00:23:00,591
Admiral Nimitz?
- Yes, sir.

293
00:23:12,313 --> 00:23:14,516
Hey that was close.
- It's a trap...

294
00:23:14,686 --> 00:23:16,513
we used to take possums like that...

295
00:23:16,687 --> 00:23:19,355
you fool them so they feel
safe and then, bang!

296
00:23:19,898 --> 00:23:23,430
We are three possums waiting...
- Come on, Prophet. Just...

297
00:23:24,273 --> 00:23:27,224
We've only got a couple of
minutes. Get the stuff.

298
00:23:55,071 --> 00:23:56,528
Hey Chief!
- Yes, Dooley?

299
00:23:56,904 --> 00:23:58,279
Your shaft's here.

300
00:24:01,530 --> 00:24:02,645
Thanks, Dooley.

301
00:24:04,448 --> 00:24:07,151
Look, Molumphry, brand
new oil pump shaft.

302
00:24:07,324 --> 00:24:09,776
Congratulations, look's like you, Tostin.

303
00:24:12,949 --> 00:24:15,320
What is that?
- Your refrigerator unit.

304
00:24:15,491 --> 00:24:17,612
That?
- We were lucky to get it.

305
00:24:17,783 --> 00:24:19,656
Man, it was cold in
that ice house.

306
00:24:21,077 --> 00:24:24,158
Look, sir, new oil pump shaft.
- Fine, fine.

307
00:24:24,327 --> 00:24:26,863
Where is Mr. Holden?
- Keeping an eye on the truck.

308
00:24:27,036 --> 00:24:28,149
Mr. Holden!

309
00:24:31,787 --> 00:24:34,738
A decent night for shopping, sir.
- Yes

310
00:24:34,912 --> 00:24:36,453
Could be something saved.

311
00:24:36,620 --> 00:24:40,449
I know where you got the Navy
supplies but what about the truck?

312
00:24:40,621 --> 00:24:44,484
I can't take credit for the
truck, sir. Ramon got it.

313
00:24:44,663 --> 00:24:46,370
Ramon??
-Ramon!

314
00:24:48,123 --> 00:24:49,865
Smile, sir. He's very sensitive.

315
00:24:50,165 --> 00:24:52,701
What?
- Captain Sherman, Sergeant Gillardo.

316
00:24:53,249 --> 00:24:55,407
I'm happy to be a member
of your crew, sir.

317
00:24:56,000 --> 00:24:58,038
What do you mean,
member of my crew??

318
00:24:58,709 --> 00:25:00,036
Well, sir...

319
00:25:00,334 --> 00:25:03,249
I promised the sergeant that if he
helped us out, you'll take him on.

320
00:25:03,793 --> 00:25:05,120
But he's a marine.

321
00:25:05,293 --> 00:25:08,706
Well, he's open to a better offer.
You'd better get back to work.

322
00:25:11,127 --> 00:25:12,408
I'll handle this.

323
00:25:15,213 --> 00:25:16,540
That man is a prisoner.

324
00:25:16,713 --> 00:25:19,711
Well, it was. You see, the prison
stockade was bombed...

325
00:25:19,880 --> 00:25:22,450
... you have no idea how
hard it was to find him.

326
00:25:22,755 --> 00:25:24,792
You mean you actually
went looking for him?

327
00:25:24,963 --> 00:25:27,370
Of course. He's the greatest
operator around here...

328
00:25:27,547 --> 00:25:30,416
... shortly after he became
General Warren's chef...

329
00:25:30,590 --> 00:25:32,830
... he went into business for himself.
- I'll bet.

330
00:25:33,008 --> 00:25:35,295
He was sole owner of
best restaurant in Manila.

331
00:25:35,967 --> 00:25:37,791
And what about the
" P " on his back?

332
00:25:37,967 --> 00:25:39,295
The " P "?
- Yes

333
00:25:39,926 --> 00:25:41,502
Oh, that...
Let's start there.

334
00:25:42,591 --> 00:25:45,923
You see, someone started prying and
found that the Marines...

335
00:25:46,093 --> 00:25:50,253
supplying all the meat and silverware...
But he's a man who can get a job done.

336
00:25:50,803 --> 00:25:54,632
There isn't a burglar, swindler,
pickpocket or fence on the island...

337
00:25:54,804 --> 00:25:56,960
that doesn't love, know,
and respect him.

338
00:25:57,137 --> 00:26:00,384
That's probably a glowing
recommendation, Mr. Holden...

339
00:26:00,555 --> 00:26:02,925
I have no intention of taking
a thief on my crew...

340
00:26:03,097 --> 00:26:05,668
He's an escaped prisoner,
a deserter.

341
00:26:06,014 --> 00:26:08,882
True, but he is also one other thing.
- What?

342
00:26:09,389 --> 00:26:11,345
He's also an informer...

343
00:26:12,140 --> 00:26:15,506
... and if we don't take him
he will tell everybody everything.

344
00:26:15,682 --> 00:26:16,631
Yeah.

345
00:26:16,808 --> 00:26:18,681
And you're in too deep
for than now, sir.

346
00:26:19,434 --> 00:26:22,004
We don't have a sales slip
for all this merchandise.

347
00:26:23,100 --> 00:26:25,636
It seems I'm boxed in,
Mr. Holden.

348
00:26:25,976 --> 00:26:29,757
You've made a wise decision, sir. I will
tell him, he will be so happy.

349
00:26:31,769 --> 00:26:32,883
Ramon!

350
00:26:39,771 --> 00:26:41,264
You have to give him credit, sir...

351
00:26:41,437 --> 00:26:43,475
... that's what I call a Supply Officer.
- What?

352
00:26:43,646 --> 00:26:45,472
I wonder where he got everything.

353
00:26:45,647 --> 00:26:49,262
There's only one way to live with the
situation. It's like watching a stripper...

354
00:26:49,439 --> 00:26:52,640
... do not ask how she does it,
just enjoy what's coming off.

355
00:26:55,607 --> 00:26:59,388
19 December, 1941.
The repairs are progressing.

356
00:26:59,566 --> 00:27:01,723
Morale is high, except
for their concern that...

357
00:27:01,901 --> 00:27:04,270
... our supply officer might
be caught and shot.

358
00:27:04,441 --> 00:27:06,349
I have mixed feelings ;...

359
00:27:06,525 --> 00:27:09,359
Lt. Holden and Sgt. Gillardo
are undoubtedly...

360
00:27:09,527 --> 00:27:11,482
the world's greatest thieves.

361
00:27:12,653 --> 00:27:13,731
Scavengers.

362
00:27:14,403 --> 00:27:16,228
To paraphrase Mr. Churchill ;...

363
00:27:16,402 --> 00:27:20,019
... " never have so few
stolen so much from so many. "

364
00:27:20,319 --> 00:27:22,774
And what they can not find
in warehouses...

365
00:27:22,946 --> 00:27:24,319
... they improvise.

366
00:27:46,244 --> 00:27:49,774
Mr. Sherman, I'm aware that there has been
wholesale scavenging...

367
00:27:49,951 --> 00:27:52,193
No, up to now I overlooked it,
knowing the position.

368
00:27:52,369 --> 00:27:55,073
Yes, sir.
- But this time you've gone too far.

369
00:27:55,411 --> 00:27:56,691
Mr. Sherman...

370
00:27:59,287 --> 00:28:01,113
I want my wall back.

371
00:28:03,205 --> 00:28:07,116
I'm not sure we have it.
- You must have it. You've got everything else.

372
00:28:07,372 --> 00:28:09,992
I do not mind a bit of
initiative but you...

373
00:28:10,165 --> 00:28:11,991
Sir, I have to get back to my boat.

374
00:28:14,331 --> 00:28:16,287
Wait a minute, I'll go with you!

375
00:29:07,010 --> 00:29:09,332
Any damage?
- No direct hit, sir.

376
00:29:09,509 --> 00:29:12,592
Concussion may have sprung some plates
in the tanks, Mr. Watson's checking.

377
00:29:12,760 --> 00:29:14,633
Or camouflage caught fire,
we cut it down.

378
00:29:14,803 --> 00:29:16,461
Were we spotted?
- Yes, sir.

379
00:29:16,636 --> 00:29:18,543
A couple gave us a close-up
look we could spit at...

380
00:29:18,719 --> 00:29:21,209
without the. 50 that's
all we could do.

381
00:29:28,055 --> 00:29:29,762
Well, I guess that does it.

382
00:29:29,931 --> 00:29:33,628
Now they'll know where to find us.
- I'm sorry, Matt.

383
00:29:34,057 --> 00:29:36,510
Sir, request permission
to get underway.

384
00:29:36,683 --> 00:29:38,091
Get underway?
- Yes

385
00:29:38,264 --> 00:29:39,177
In that?

386
00:29:39,348 --> 00:29:41,803
I can get as far as Cebu and
complete repairs.

387
00:29:41,975 --> 00:29:43,930
Cebu??
- That's only 400 miles.

388
00:29:44,100 --> 00:29:47,217
You'd be in trouble if it was 400 feet.
You're in no condition to go out.

389
00:29:47,393 --> 00:29:50,391
We've made amazing progress.
- You can not even submerge...

390
00:29:50,560 --> 00:29:53,724
If you try running on top in
the daylight you're a dead duck.

391
00:29:54,269 --> 00:29:55,846
Molumphry!
- Yes, sir?

392
00:29:56,020 --> 00:29:59,101
Can this boat go down?
- Like a rock, sir.

393
00:29:59,602 --> 00:30:02,471
Mr. Watson, how are the plates?
- Tight as a drum, sir.

394
00:30:02,645 --> 00:30:05,763
And the engines, Tostin?
- Factory fresh, sir.

395
00:30:06,146 --> 00:30:07,390
What do you say, sir?

396
00:30:07,772 --> 00:30:10,853
Take your scavengers and
these liars and get out.

397
00:30:11,022 --> 00:30:12,765
Yes, sir.
- But one stipulation.

398
00:30:12,940 --> 00:30:15,475
You will engage no enemy shipping,
including lifeboats.

399
00:30:15,648 --> 00:30:19,772
If you see someone swimming
in the water avoid him.

400
00:30:19,941 --> 00:30:21,137
Yes, sir.
- Good luck.

401
00:30:21,315 --> 00:30:22,346
Thank you, sir.

402
00:30:23,150 --> 00:30:24,311
Matt.

403
00:30:24,775 --> 00:30:27,773
Is this what's left of
my wall?

404
00:30:27,943 --> 00:30:29,104
I wouldn't know, sir.

405
00:30:29,276 --> 00:30:31,066
I would appreciate at least...

406
00:30:31,234 --> 00:30:33,309
... getting my window back.
- Yes, sir.

407
00:30:38,945 --> 00:30:40,318
Can we make it?

408
00:30:40,486 --> 00:30:42,810
Well, we have No. 1
engine in shape.

409
00:30:42,987 --> 00:30:45,392
No. 2 I'll tell you about
when it's put back together.

410
00:30:45,570 --> 00:30:46,649
How about three and four?

411
00:30:46,821 --> 00:30:49,108
I've been using them for
parts for one and two.

412
00:30:49,280 --> 00:30:52,896
I am a religious man, Captain, I
believe God will get us through.

413
00:30:53,490 --> 00:30:56,274
Of course, He'll have to give
us his undivided attention.

414
00:30:57,698 --> 00:30:58,860
Mr. Watson!

415
00:30:59,032 --> 00:31:01,900
Be ready to get underway when
Mr. Holden and his gang get back.

416
00:31:02,073 --> 00:31:03,651
Aye, sir.
- Any idea where they went?

417
00:31:03,825 --> 00:31:06,147
No, sir. When the air raid
started they took off.

418
00:31:06,451 --> 00:31:10,611
All Mr. Holden said was:
" in confusion there is profit. "

419
00:31:24,035 --> 00:31:25,778
Obviously the same
guys who...

420
00:31:26,079 --> 00:31:29,741
Sir, we just got a call from the
Security Officer, and he's furious.

421
00:31:30,788 --> 00:31:32,162
Why? What's wrong?

422
00:31:32,330 --> 00:31:34,570
Apparently someone
stole his safe.

423
00:31:48,334 --> 00:31:49,911
What happened, sir?

424
00:31:51,042 --> 00:31:55,203
Douglas, I think we've been victims
of Sherman's march to the sea.

425
00:31:56,418 --> 00:31:58,989
Make all preparations
for getting underway.

426
00:31:59,252 --> 00:32:00,117
Aye aye, sir.

427
00:32:00,294 --> 00:32:01,918
Station the watch.

428
00:32:02,252 --> 00:32:03,877
Lookouts to posts for sea.

429
00:32:09,505 --> 00:32:11,460
Ready to get underway?
- Ready, sir.

430
00:32:13,923 --> 00:32:15,166
Get ready on No. 1 engine.

431
00:32:15,339 --> 00:32:17,745
Maneuvering, Bridge.
Get ready on No. 1 engine.

432
00:32:37,635 --> 00:32:39,010
Ready on No. 1 engine.

433
00:32:39,177 --> 00:32:41,381
Maneuvering, Bridge.
Get ready on No. 1 engine.

434
00:33:06,892 --> 00:33:08,089
Any time they're ready.

435
00:33:08,267 --> 00:33:10,305
Maneuvering, Bridge.
Any time you're ready.

436
00:33:38,647 --> 00:33:40,887
Mr. Holden! What
the devil is that?

437
00:33:41,064 --> 00:33:44,348
A witch doctor, sir. Ramon found
him in the hills. We hired him.

438
00:33:44,940 --> 00:33:46,220
You hired him?

439
00:33:46,899 --> 00:33:49,685
To ward off evil spirits
and wish us a safe journey.

440
00:33:49,859 --> 00:33:52,312
I figured we could use all
the help we could get, sir.

441
00:34:06,861 --> 00:34:07,892
Hey hey hey hey.

442
00:34:09,154 --> 00:34:10,185
Cut that out.

443
00:34:10,363 --> 00:34:13,609
Mr. Holden! Will you tell
this fella...

444
00:34:13,780 --> 00:34:15,651
I can't hear myself think!

445
00:34:16,447 --> 00:34:18,154
Go away, please!

446
00:34:20,156 --> 00:34:23,570
Get away from my boat!
Get away from my... !

447
00:34:33,367 --> 00:34:34,361
Single up all lines.

448
00:34:34,534 --> 00:34:35,529
Single one.

449
00:34:36,867 --> 00:34:38,065
Single four.

450
00:34:41,910 --> 00:34:42,988
Right full rudder.

451
00:34:46,412 --> 00:34:48,285
All ahead one third,
starboard back one third.

452
00:34:48,455 --> 00:34:50,279
All ahead one third,
starboard back one third.

453
00:34:50,454 --> 00:34:51,450
What a character.

454
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:09,409
All stop. Shift your rudder.

455
00:35:09,583 --> 00:35:11,076
All stop. Shift your rudder.

456
00:35:25,128 --> 00:35:26,953
All ahead two thirds.
Ease your rudder.

457
00:35:27,128 --> 00:35:28,870
All ahead two thirds.
Ease your rudder.

458
00:35:56,175 --> 00:35:57,717
You'll never make it.

459
00:36:15,472 --> 00:36:17,924
Tostin is still fighting with
the No. 2 engine, sir.

460
00:36:18,097 --> 00:36:19,424
Sounds like he's losing.

461
00:36:20,264 --> 00:36:21,638
How's the battery charge?

462
00:36:21,805 --> 00:36:23,963
Just enough for
a trim dive.

463
00:36:24,348 --> 00:36:25,546
Okay to try it?

464
00:36:25,723 --> 00:36:28,972
Not now, wait for the dawn,
we have to take it down then.

465
00:36:29,599 --> 00:36:31,340
We will have to try it sometime.

466
00:36:32,349 --> 00:36:34,387
I'm not complaining, sir.
I had my choice.

467
00:36:34,558 --> 00:36:35,339
Of what?

468
00:36:36,016 --> 00:36:37,558
I could have gone
to West Point.

469
00:36:41,268 --> 00:36:42,382
Careful, sir.

470
00:36:51,061 --> 00:36:52,887
Well, now is the time.

471
00:36:53,062 --> 00:36:54,259
Let's take her down.

472
00:36:54,728 --> 00:36:55,594
Aye, sir.

473
00:36:55,854 --> 00:36:57,680
Clear the bridge.
- Clear the bridge.

474
00:36:57,855 --> 00:36:59,134
Number one.
- Aye.

475
00:36:59,313 --> 00:37:00,511
Number Two.
- Aye.

476
00:37:00,689 --> 00:37:02,349
Number Three.
- Number Four.

477
00:37:11,024 --> 00:37:13,513
Make depth five-eight feet.
- Aye, sir. Five-eight feet.

478
00:37:19,067 --> 00:37:20,182
Five-eight feet.

479
00:37:25,985 --> 00:37:26,980
Check your bubble.

480
00:37:40,405 --> 00:37:41,602
Close all vents.

481
00:37:52,449 --> 00:37:53,611
All ahead one third.

482
00:37:53,783 --> 00:37:55,062
All ahead one third.

483
00:38:03,327 --> 00:38:04,405
Periscope depth.

484
00:38:05,952 --> 00:38:08,737
Let's check for leaks.
Take her down to 100 feet.

485
